{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "CAISO regulation service participation requirements eligibility qualification telemetry AGC telemetry meter telemetry performance requirements market participation regulation",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": 2000,
      "year_end": 2026,
      "range_type": "between"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "0d4dc6a8-ffe2-40ad-8c38-2ff7ab456d8b",
        "score": 0.5739944,
        "text": "The document page discusses California's greenhouse gas allowance market under the state's cap-and-trade program, which was applied to the wholesale electric market in 2013. It explains that greenhouse gas compliance costs are factored into resource commitment costs, default energy bids, and generated bids. The energy imbalance market transfers serving ISO load are also attributed to these compliance costs. The document details how the ISO uses a calculated greenhouse gas allowance index price as a daily measure for allowance costs, based on the average of two market-based indices. Further details on compliance in the energy imbalance market are referenced in another section.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2017/page_63.jpg",
          "page_num": 63,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1e7c40bc-8383-4b5c-963a-6e9ac31d6e1b",
        "score": 0.5632714,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated August 2021. It includes Figure 1.34, which shows the Aliso gas nomogram binding status in day-ahead and real-time markets on October 4, 2020. The graph displays limits and cleared values for day-ahead, 15-minute, and 5-minute intervals in megawatts (MW) over a 24-hour period.\n\nSection 1.2.8 discusses California's greenhouse gas allowance market, which is part of the state's cap-and-trade program applied to the wholesale electric market since 2013. It explains how greenhouse gas compliance costs are integrated into cost-based bids and local market power mitigation of energy. These costs are attributed to resources in the energy imbalance market to ensure compliance with the cap-and-trade program and mandatory reporting regulations. Compliance obligations are determined by the ISO's optimization based on energy bids and greenhouse gas bid adders. Further details are available in Section 3.4 of the report.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_78.jpg",
          "page_num": 78,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7db8ebd3-aa51-4b3c-9977-19a7f394fdfe",
        "score": 0.55527955,
        "text": "The document discusses the resource adequacy program for the California ISO system, aimed at ensuring sufficient capacity for reliable grid operation. It involves collaboration with the California Energy Commission (CEC), California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC), and other local regulatory authorities to set procurement obligations for load-serving entities.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Purpose**: To ensure the grid has enough capacity to operate reliably, compensating fixed costs of existing generators through bilateral transactions.\n\n2. **Program Components**: \n   - System resource capacity for peak demand.\n   - Local resource capacity for specific areas with limited import capability.\n   - Flexible resource capacity for ramping periods.\n\n3. **Regulatory Requirements**: \n   - Load-serving entities must demonstrate procurement of adequate capacity.\n   - CPUC-jurisdictional entities must show 90% compliance for summer months and 100% for monthly obligations.\n   - The planning reserve margin (PRM) was set between 20-22.5% for 2022-2023.\n\nThe document also highlights the role of regulatory bodies in setting and enforcing these requirements to maintain grid reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_226.jpg",
          "page_num": 226,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f042b8c8-f6d0-4d03-9b54-89f32e75d21f",
        "score": 0.55257493,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2022. It includes a graph (Figure 1.34) showing the Aliso gas nomogram binding status in day-ahead and real-time markets on July 16, 2021. The graph compares limits and cleared values for day-ahead, 15-minute, and 5-minute intervals in megawatts (MW) over a 24-hour period.\n\nSection 1.2.8 discusses California's greenhouse gas allowance market under the state's cap-and-trade program, implemented in the wholesale electric market in 2013. It explains how greenhouse gas compliance costs are factored into cost-based bids and local market power mitigation. These costs are attributed to resources in the Western Energy Imbalance Market (WEIM) and are reported to resource scheduling coordinators. The section also references further details on greenhouse gas compliance in Section 3.3 of the report.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_79.jpg",
          "page_num": 79,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ad24eee-183b-4e69-a4a2-d3881db1db1d",
        "score": 0.5456271,
        "text": "The document outlines the regulatory requirements and obligations for resource adequacy in the California ISO market. It details how the ISO collaborates with the CPUC and other authorities to set requirements for load-serving entities based on forecasted peak loads, including a planning reserve margin. Load-serving entities must demonstrate compliance through annual and monthly supply plans.\n\nFor annual showings, entities must prove they have procured 90% of their resource adequacy obligations for the summer months and 100% for monthly obligations. Plans are submitted to the ISO in advance of the compliance year or month.\n\nThe document also describes bidding and scheduling obligations. Scheduling coordinators must make resource adequacy capacity available in the ISO markets through:\n\n- **Day-ahead energy and ancillary services market**: All available capacity must be offered here.\n- **Residual unit commitment process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW.\n- **Real-time market**: Committed resources must be offered here, including short-start units.\n\nResource adequacy capacity not scheduled in the day-ahead market is not required in the real-time market unless specified. In 2018, half of the capacity was from resources that had to bid into the market each hour, except when unavailable due to outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_241.jpg",
          "page_num": 241,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a2de032c-dc01-4749-bc54-eed033d7d2f2",
        "score": 0.5424373,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2023 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2024. It includes a chart (Figure 1.31) comparing yearly average natural gas prices at various locations to the Henry Hub average for 2022 and 2023.\n\nThe text discusses California's greenhouse gas allowance market under the state's cap-and-trade program, implemented in the wholesale electric market in 2013. It explains that greenhouse gas compliance costs are factored into cost-based bids, affecting energy resources in the California ISO balancing area and other areas in the Western Energy Imbalance Market (WEIM). These costs are attributed to resources participating in the WEIM and serve the California ISO or other balancing areas, ensuring compliance with the cap-and-trade program and reporting regulations.\n\nThe document also mentions that greenhouse gas compliance costs are reported to resource scheduling coordinators and that a calculated greenhouse gas allowance index price is used daily to measure these costs. Further details on compliance are available in Section 3.6 of the report.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_80.jpg",
          "page_num": 80,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c89e033f-e299-4c22-a74f-ba87ff0750b2",
        "score": 0.53314817,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements and processes for local resource adequacy as determined by the California ISO. It explains that local resource adequacy requirements are based on an annual technical study, which identifies the minimum megawatts needed for reliability in local capacity areas. The ISO allocates these obligations to scheduling coordinators based on each entity's share of transmission access charge area load.\n\nFor CPUC-jurisdictional load-serving entities, compliance involves adopting the CPUC's technical study results and demonstrating 100% procurement of local resource adequacy requirements monthly. Supply plans must be submitted by October's end, and entities must update load migration data monthly from May to December.\n\nThe document also discusses bidding and scheduling obligations, requiring that procured capacity be available for various market commitments. Additionally, it includes an analysis of capacity availability during summer peak hours, comparing CPUC-established requirements to actual market bids in 2018.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_251.jpg",
          "page_num": 251,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a9ae3914-9e7c-4005-9b85-8802add8a912",
        "score": 0.52782154,
        "text": "The document is a table of contents from the \"2023 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring for the California ISO, dated July 2024. It outlines various figures and topics related to energy market performance and monitoring. Key areas include:\n\n1. **Real-time Imbalance Energy**: Charges and offsets by month and balancing area.\n2. **Congestion Costs**: Daily and monthly congestion costs and offsets.\n3. **Ancillary Services**: Costs, requirements, and market clearing prices.\n4. **Residual Supply Index**: Analysis of supply with largest suppliers excluded.\n5. **Market Mitigation**: Incremental energy mitigated in real-time markets.\n6. **Gas-Fired Capacity**: Day-ahead and real-time gas-fired capacity under proxy cost options.\n7. **Congestion and Price Separation**: Impact on day-ahead and real-time markets.\n8. **Auction Revenues**: Comparison with congestion payments and CRR auctions.\n9. **Residual Unit Commitment**: Adjustments and procurement details.\n10. **Load Adjustments**: Frequency and distribution of positive and negative load adjustments.\n11. **Resource Adequacy**: Hourly adequacy capacity and requirements.\n\nThe document provides a comprehensive overview of market operations, focusing on energy costs, market efficiency, and regulatory compliance.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_10.jpg",
          "page_num": 10,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9ce1ba4c-08fd-4e7b-9a88-bf1605eb44d1",
        "score": 0.5277161,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated August 2021. It includes Table 3.3, which shows the frequency of congestion on the energy imbalance market transfer constraints for 2020. The table compares congestion in the 15-minute and 5-minute markets across various entities, such as BANC, Arizona Public Service, and others. Congestion percentages are provided for both \"from area\" and \"into area\" categories.\n\nThe section titled \"3.4 Greenhouse gas compliance costs\" discusses the background of energy delivery to California under the cap-and-trade regulation. It explains that participating resources must submit separate bids for compliance costs, which are included in the energy imbalance market dispatch optimization. The optimization aims to minimize system load costs while accounting for greenhouse gas compliance. The greenhouse gas price is set at the bid of the marginal megawatt serving California load. Scheduling coordinators receive revenue as compensation for compliance obligations, based on the cleared 15-minute market greenhouse gas quantity.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_151.jpg",
          "page_num": 151,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8e099f90-73f7-4a0d-b3f1-1eeec9222e37",
        "score": 0.5241007,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2024, and discusses monthly assistance energy transfer surcharges and greenhouse gas compliance costs.\n\n1. **Figure 3.31**: Displays a bar graph of the monthly assistance energy transfer surcharge for 2023. The surcharges are highest in September, followed by August and July, with minimal amounts from October to December.\n\n2. **Section 3.6: Greenhouse Gas Compliance Costs**:\n   - **Background**: Under the Western Energy Imbalance Market (WEIM) design, all energy delivered to serve California's load is subject to California\u2019s cap-and-trade regulation. Participating resources must submit bids representing the cost of compliance for energy attributed to serving California. These bids are included in the WEIM dispatch optimization.\n   - The optimization process minimizes the cost of serving system load while considering greenhouse gas compliance costs for energy delivered to California.\n   - In November 2018, a policy change was implemented to address secondary dispatch concerns. Secondary dispatch involves low-emitting resources outside California scheduling imports into California. The policy limits the capacity deemed delivered into California to the difference between a resource\u2019s base schedule and its economic bid limit.\n\nThe page also references further information available on the California Air Resources Board\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2023/page_190.jpg",
          "page_num": 190,
          "title": "2023 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

